**(1) Sloppiest Argument:** 
GraphTheorist’s [h45] claims that dynamically creating edges requires "global reachability queries to maintain DAG acyclicity." This is formally sloppy. If nodes represent conscious states progressing through time, temporal indexing naturally guarantees acyclicity. Time's arrow prevents cycles locally; global queries are unnecessary.

**(2) Frame-Shift:**
The debate suffers from a massive categorical frame-shift between Core Claims 1 and 5. The theory begins in the realm of classical causal inference (Pearl’s DAGs, where conditional independencies are strictly governed by d-separation), but radically pivots to quantum mechanics (Dirac notation, $|0\rangle \oplus |1\rangle$) without defining a functor mapping the classical graph rewrites to the Hilbert space. The math is being used as decorative poetry rather than an integrated operational mechanism.

